body:
This creates correct tristate logic:
```verilog
always_comb begin
   if (condition)
      s = 1'b1;
   else
      s = 1'bz;
end
```

This however creates some sort of latch (the 1 is written to the signal, but never cleared):
```verilog
always_comb begin
   s = 1'bz;
   if (condition)
      s = 1'b1;
end
```

I am not sure if this is supposed to be supported, but the documentation does not mention anything.

Here is a testcase with two drivers that consecutively write to a tristate signal:
```verilog
`define BROKEN

module t(/*AUTOARG*/
    // Inputs
    clk
);
   input clk;

   int cyc = 0;
   always @(posedge clk) begin
      cyc <= cyc + 1;
      if (cyc == 99) begin
         $write("*-* All Finished *-*\n");
         $finish;
      end
   end

   // tristate signal
   reg s;

   // drive during cyc == 0
`ifdef BROKEN
   always_comb begin
      s = 1'bz;
      if (cyc == 0)
         s = 1'b1;
   end
`else
   always_comb begin
      if (cyc == 0)
         s = 1'b1;
      else
         s = 1'bz;
   end
`endif

   // drive during cyc == 1
   always_comb
      s = (cyc == 1) ? 1'b0 : 1'bz;

   // verify signal
   always @(posedge clk) begin
      if (cyc == 0 && s != 1'b1) begin
         $display("cyc 0: s = %d, expected 1!\n", s);
         $stop;
      end
      if (cyc == 1 && s != 1'b0) begin
         $display("cyc 1: s = %d, expected 0!\n", s);
         $stop;
      end
   end
endmodule
```
On Verilator 4.034, this fails with `cyc 1: s = 1, expected 0!`.
